 <!-- Introduction -->
 <!-- The introduction should start as shown: -->
 <purpose>
   <p>
     This part of ISO 10303 specifies an application module to define
a schematic drawing and its administrative information. A schematic drawing is
a schematic element that is a complete drawing.</p>
<p> This part of ISO 10303 also defines page
connectors, which provide the links between different schematic drawings, or
between different parts of the same schematic drawing.</p>
 </purpose>

 <!-- Items in scope -->
 <inscope>
<li><p>a complete schematic drawing with its administrative data;</p>
<note number="1">This capability is provided by the referenced <module_ref linkend="schematic_element:1_scope">Schematic_element</module_ref> 
and <module_ref linkend="drawing_structure_and_administration:1_scope">Drawing_structure_and_administration</module_ref> application
modules.</note>
</li>
<li><p>page connectors, and their relationships.</p>
</li> </inscope>

 <!-- Items out of scope -->
 <outscope>
<li><p>a library of schematic element definitions (i.e. a symbol library);</p>
<note number="2">A library of schematic element definitions is within
the scope of the <module_ref linkend="schematic_element_library:1_scope">Schematic_element_library</module_ref> application module. </note>
</li>
<li><p>the relationship between a schematic element and the thing that it
stands for.</p>
<note number="3">The relationship between a schematic element and a
product or activity that it stands for is within the scope of the
<module_ref linkend="symbolization_by_schematic_element:1_scope">Symbolization_by_schematic_element</module_ref> application module.</note>
</li>
 </outscope>

